metadata.description:
This piece is an abstraction and a reflection on the last era, on all that we have built and become. Are we proud of it or has it just been the result of iterating through the days? Since the technology boom, we have experienced great improvements, but perhaps also massive ...mistakes?â€¨â€¨

Inspired by textbooks of the 80s, with elements that remind us of industry, technology, networks and systems, "Unsolicited abstraction of modern times" invites us to question our work to date. Has everything really changed?

metadata.name: Permutation City #112
metadata.description:
The work is inspired by the novel Permutation City by Greg Egan, the author of the hard science fiction.

It raises the issue of whether we can in principle understand that we exist in reality or in a simulation.

According to the Theory of Dust (which is described in the novel), the universe is simulatable and all other possible universes are equally as real as ours, emerging spontaneously from their own mathematical self-consistency. Human consciousness isÂ Turing-computable, which means that consciousness can be also produced by a computer program.

TheÂ AutoverseÂ is anÂ artificial lifeÂ simulator, a massive complex cellular automaton universe, producing cities and the consciousness of human copies.

Gradually, due to failures and a lack of computing power, the idea of the reliability of such universes is destroyed. 

Spaces crumble, cities become fluid and drain down, turning into dust and digital glitch.

Thanks to Yulikolay for helping with code, using p5.Riso.js library for generating files suitable for risograph printing.
Source images for permutation cities are made with a help of DALLÂ·E mini neural network.

metadata.name: Phantoms #177
metadata.description:
Phantoms is a series of hazy memories of distant places. Some tranquil, others sinister, each scene is as much defined by what is revealed as by what remains unseen.

In this collection I aim to juxtapose hard and soft. Blocky shapes form the core of the compositions. Upon these surfaces, soft textures appear to flow and drip over the sides. Varying levels of opacity, lighting, and fog effects further soften the scenes to create an atmospheric, dream-like quality. By remaining semi-abstract, each of the color palettes are given the space to influence the mood dramatically.

metadata.name: Abstract Temples #16
metadata.description:
Giorgio de Chirico was a prominent influence on the Surrealist movement. De Chiricoâ€™s art portrays dream-like and distorted worlds that encourage viewers to explore their subconscious. 

I am fascinated by the different ways artists have found to express esoteric concepts. In particular, I am interested in how artists like Giorgio de Chirico have used light and color to create ethereal images. 

I believe that the Abstract Temples project is a perfect example of how generative art can be used to create metaphysical artwork. By invoking the visual language of the dream world, these images invite you to explore the nebulous relationship between external and internal space.

In addition to the influence of Giorgio de Chirico, I would also like to credit James Turrell as an inspiration for this project. Turrell is an artist who creates installations that play with our perception of light and space. Turrellâ€™s work has profoundly impacted my understanding of how art can create an immersive and disorienting experience. 

Each temple room is randomly generated from a selection of 16 templates. The templates include a variety of randomized features, including the color palette, celestial objects, design variations, and other effects. They also contain a rare secret. 

This project was created with p5js. 

Features:
-16 room templates
-18 color palettes
-Celestial objects
-Secrets

metadata.name: Future Galaxies #2
metadata.description: Modern science tells us that the vastness of the universe exceeds imagination. From the perspective of physics theory, there are billions galaxies each containing millions billions stars. Although we cannot see some celestial bodies through human lens, there are many heavenly lights created inside us which humans do not notice. This piece reflects an approach to imagine new forms of life.

metadata.name: Impending Cloths #38
metadata.description:
IC makes use of fabric's potential for contrasts.
The same piece of cloth can seem to be falling, perfectly still and ready to be blown away, all at the same time.
It can look "very digital" while also achieving a high degree of texture. And so on, and so forth. Contrast and potential.
Also, "h" can be pressed to download in high resolution, although it may take up to a minute.

metadata.name: Reconnaissance #16
metadata.description:
An immense quiet accompanies a sense of looming futility while peering down across vast new worlds. What use is there in discovering and documenting these unknown places? Who would care to seek out lifeless lands lost in the cosmos?

Any civilization capable of such reconnaissance might seem above the little hope that barren lands may bring. Unless, of course, there is a hope of answering the most desperate of needs: Finding a New Home.

Were these images captured by humans on Earth, or on Mars, or somewhere even further away in distance and probability? Maybe theyâ€™re recon from another planetâ€™s civilization â€” one that shares our struggle to find true harmony with the world they have.

Inspired by the remarkable satellite imagery in the compendium â€œThis is Mars,â€ Reconnaissance suggests what may lie outside our habitable lands â€” and that we risk missing what's already here while being compelled to look further and further for whatâ€™s next.
